Giussani acutely points out that most of the following examples seem not to agree with the rule given. A spider’s web, for instance, must, owing to its length, touch many atoms of soul: it is much larger than the point ofa needle, to which atoms of the soul respond reedily enough. In this case the important element is lightness (cf. 1. 387), not smallness. It seems likely that, according to Epicurus, there are no atonis of soul on the absolute sursace of the body, so that a very light object, even

Α if of some length, touches atoms of the body only, whereas a heavier object, by carrying its impression deeper, does reach atoms of the soul. And I think Lucr. may have intended to express this here: in fact, the interualla are not of superficies, but of profrurdity.

381. incusem aretum has generally been explained by the use of creta as a cosmetic. Giussani thinks that there is a reference to a practical jolre ol street-boys (see n. to l. 196) who, unperceived, strike people on the back with an object marked with chalk; but surely vestibus would be needed then, not membris.
